Lambda functions, also known as anonymous functions, are a feature in many programming languages, including R. In R, a lambda function is a function that is not bound to a name. This means that it can be created and used on the fly without defining it in the standard way with a name. Lambda functions are particularly useful for short, one-off functions that are used as arguments to other functions, like in apply family functions or in operations that involve the pipe operator (|&gt;).

